<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4912&amp;p=43830#p43830"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[New chips are too fast?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4912&amp;p=43830#p43830"><![CDATA[
This forum is pretty quiet recently, so I though I would share something with you.<br /><br />My flash cartridge had a very interesting bug, the CPLD chip was too fast! It would cause graphics corruption in certain games like Donkey Kong Country, and if I turned on the 'turbo bits' to speed up the chip it wouldn't work at all.<br /><br />My theory is the different logic level (its a 3.3v part thats 5v tolerant) and faster speed made it turn off the bus buffer and address decoder before the graphics chip was actually finished reading, like a hold time violation. <br /><br />I fixed the problem 100% by soldering a 100pf cap from the cart's CEn to GND. I have heard of a similar problem with the PowerPak, so I wonder if this could help with that.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3686">cybertron</a> — Mon Mar 02, 2009 9:13 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
